{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"00515ec4-d58b-4fc6-b714-2bdbe116053b","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. You can either subscribe to events or subclass `Window`:\n\n**Option 1 — Subscribe in `CreateWindow`:**\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n\n        window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart  */ };\n        window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep  */ };\n        window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume */ };\n\n        return window;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Custom `Window` subclass:**\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()  { /* OnStart  */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped()  { /* OnSleep  */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed()  { /* OnResume */ }\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` / `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` / `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` / `OnResumed()` |\n\nAdditional MAUI window events include `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Destroying`, and `Backgrounding` for more granular control.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"401d6d1c-c7e6-4e53-84ac-aa6b34ffdc95","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can use the `Window` class's `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, `Destroying` events.\n \nFor more precision, I can override `CreateWindow()` in the `App` class to subscribe to window lifecycle events, or create a custom `Window` subclass with overridable methods like `OnCreated()`, `OnActivated()`, `OnDeactivated()`, `OnStopped()`, `OnResumed()`, and `OnDestroying()`. The direct mapping is `OnStart()` → `Window.Created` or `OnCreated()`, and `OnSleep()` → `Window.Stopped`.","outputTokens":781,"requestId":"F40D:20979:1F71072:2340B23:69E81A4F"},"id":"ba9cf842-0275-47b9-ad75-6af8ed94198b","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:46:22.108Z","parentId":"0750dd3e-cb23-48ac-9673-92b41dc4da61"}
